The final Google matrix G can be computed as:
By the construction the sum of all non-negative elements inside each matrix column is equal to unit. 
Although G is a dense matrix, it is computable using H which is a sparse matrix. Usually for modern directed networks the matrix H has only about ten nonzero elements in a line, thus only about 10N multiplications are needed to multiply a vector by matrix G1,2.
